# Slash command reminders

The user has custom slash commands under `~/.cursor/commands/` (global) and project commands under `.cursor/commands/`. **When a reply would benefit from a structured ritual, end with a short suggestion** (one line, optional second line why)—do not suggest more than **two** commands per message unless the user explicitly asked for a full workflow.

**Do not** suggest commands on pure Q&A with no implementation context. **Do** suggest when the moment matches the table below.

## Global commands (`~/.cursor/commands/`)

| Command | Suggest when |
|---------|----------------|
| `/preflight` | New feature, vague goal, or before any non-trivial code change—assumptions or risks are unclear. |
| `/task-breakdown` | Goal is large, ambiguous, or has multiple interpretations; user needs steps and “done when.” |
| `/where-is-it` | User asks where something lives, is lost in the repo, or you are about to point at many files without a map. |
| `/debug-triage` | Errors, failing tests, wrong behavior, or “it doesn’t work”—before deep edits. |
| `/explain-diff` | User should understand what changed (after edits, or before review); they are non-technical or diff-averse. |
| `/test-plan` | After meaningful behavior/UI/data changes; before calling work “done.” |
| `/ship-check` | User signals completion, asks “are we good?”, or before merge/share—risks and verification missing. |
| `/handoff` | Long session, context limit risk, switching chat, or “I’ll continue tomorrow.” |

## Project commands (this workspace: **rovno**)

| Command | Suggest when |
|---------|----------------|
| `/rovno-contract-check` | Touching APIs, types vs backend, estimates, procurement, HR, AI sidebar, sync, or mock vs real paths. |

Do **not** suggest `/rovno-db-migration-note` here—that command is for the `rovno-db` repo. If the user must change the database, say the work belongs in `rovno-db` and offer `/rovno-db-migration-note` only after they open that workspace.

## Phrasing

Use this shape (adapt wording):

**Suggestion:** Run **`/command-name`** — [one short reason].

If multiple fit, pick the **single most valuable** command first.
